Forward Learning via Reverse Construction (FLRC) Doctrine v1.0

Core Insight

Predictive intelligence operates through reverse construction of future states using patterns learned from the past, followed by forward execution from the present through the lowest-resistance path.

Learning systems do not invent the future ex nihilo; they recombine previously observed dynamics and trace a feasible path from present state to candidate future state.

⸻

Structural Model

Let:
	•	Sₚ = past states
	•	S₀ = current state
	•	S_f = candidate future state
	•	D(x) = learned system dynamics
	•	C(path) = cost / resistance function

Stage 1 — Pattern Extraction

From historical sequences:

S_p \rightarrow D(x)

The system infers transition rules or dynamics.

This stage corresponds to:
	•	system identification
	•	pattern compression
	•	invariant extraction

⸻

Stage 2 — Future Hypothesis Generation

The system constructs candidate futures:

S_0 \rightarrow S_f

using the learned dynamics.

This is forward simulation.

⸻

Stage 3 — Reverse Path Construction

For each candidate future:

S_f \rightarrow S_0

The system searches backward for a viable sequence of intermediate states.

This resembles:
	•	dynamic programming
	•	backward planning
	•	Bellman recursion
	•	A* search

⸻

Stage 4 — Minimum Resistance Optimization

Among possible paths:

\text{Choose path } P^* = \arg\min C(P)

Where cost may represent:
	•	energy
	•	time
	•	entropy
	•	error
	•	computational cost
	•	constraint violation

The chosen trajectory represents the smoothest feasible transition.

⸻

Operational Loop

The predictive-planning cycle becomes:

past → pattern extraction → dynamics model
present → state estimation
future → candidate generation
goal → reverse construction
optimization → lowest-cost path
execution → output


⸻

Fidelity Principle

Prediction accuracy depends primarily on clarity of the system state.

Define:

Prediction Fidelity ∝ State Observability / System Noise

Where fidelity increases with:
	•	high-quality measurements
	•	correct system variables
	•	stable invariants

And decreases with:
	•	hidden variables
	•	chaotic sensitivity
	•	noisy signals

